<li id="cite_note-note-suffix-v-5"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-note-suffix-v_5-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="/wiki/Standards_organization" title="Standards organization">Standards organizations</a> recommend that photometric quantities be denoted with a subscript "v" (for "visual") to avoid confusion with radiometric or <a href="/wiki/Photon" title="Photon">photon</a> quantities. For example: <i>USA Standard Letter Symbols for Illuminating Engineering</i> USAS Z7.1-1967, Y10.18-1967</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-note-dimension-symbol-6"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-note-dimension-symbol_6-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The symbols in this column denote <a href="/wiki/Dimension_of_a_physical_quantity" class="mw-redirect" title="Dimension of a physical quantity">dimensions</a>; "<b>L</b>", "<b>T</b>" and "<b>J</b>" are for length, time and luminous intensity respectively, not the symbols for the <a href="/wiki/Units_of_measurement" class="mw-redirect" title="Units of measurement">units</a> litre, tesla and joule.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-note-alternative-symbol-photometric-7"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-note-alternative-symbol-photometric_7-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-alternative-symbol-photometric_7-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-alternative-symbol-photometric_7-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Alternative symbols sometimes seen: <i>W</i> for luminous energy, <i>P</i> or <i>F</i> for luminous flux, and <i>&#961;</i> for luminous efficacy of a source.</span>
</li>
</ol></div></div>
